p with than the annoyance of a good example.', 286, 0), (396236, 'The only thing to do with good advice is to pass it on. It is never of any use to oneself.', 40, 0), (396237, 'A good scare is worth more to a man than good advice.', 20175, 0), (396238, 'There is little serenity comparable to the serenity of the inexperienced giving advice to the experienced.', 33, 0), (396239, 'Advice is seldom welcome  and those who want it the most always like it the least.', 62413, 0), (396240, 'It is well enough  when one is talking to a friend  to lodge in an odd word by way of counsel now and then  but there is something mighty irksome in its staring upon one in a letter  where one ought to see only kind words and friendly remembrances.', 62414, 0), (396241, 'Men of much depth of mind can bear a great deal of counsel  for it does not easily deface their own character  nor render their purposes indistinct.', 62415, 0), (396242, 'Have more than thou showest  Speak less than thou knowest.', 13, 0), (396243, 'What you don''t see with your eyes  don''t invent with your tongue.', 29291, 0), (396244, 'If you keep your mind sufficiently open  people will throw a lot of rubbish into it.', 62416, 0), (396245, 'Don''t fight forces  use them.', 62417, 0), (396246, 'Drink nothing without seeing it  sign nothing without reading it.', 8413, 0), (396247, 'What is important is to keep learning  to enjoy challenge  and to tolerate ambiguity. In the end there are no certain answers.', 62418, 0), (396248, 'Simplicity  simplicity  simplicity. I say  let your affairs be as two or three  and not a hundred or a thousand  instead of a million count half a dozen  and keep your accounts on your thumbnail.', 1049, 0), (396249, 'You must not think  sir  to catch old birds with chaff.', 25285, 0), (396250, 'Never give advice in a crowd.', 42902, 0);
